Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | API | Pattern | Replacement |
|----------|-----|---------|-------------|
| `RunLoop` | `while(true)` + `WaitOne()` | Cancellable work loop + blocking call | `CancellationToken` in loop + `WaitHandle.WaitAny` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Abort()` | Fallback forced termination | Remove — cooperative cancellation handles it |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _thread = new Thread(() => RunLoop(_cts.Token));
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns immediately when token is cancelled,
            // replacing both Thread.Interrupt and Thread.Abort
            WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items — fixes a race in the original
            // where rapid Enqueue calls could leave items stranded
            List<string> items;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                items = new List<string>(_queue);
                _queue.Clear();
            }

            foreach (var item in items)
            {
                if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                    break;
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();       // signals token.WaitHandle, wakes WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);  // wait for graceful exit — no Abort fallback needed
        Dispose();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Interrupt()` → `CancellationToken.WaitHandle`** — `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` unblocks when *either* a new event arrives *or* cancellation is requested. No interrupt needed.

2. **`Thread.Abort()` → removed entirely** — cooperative cancellation means the loop exits voluntarily. The `Join(5000)` will succeed because the loop checks `IsCancellationRequested`.

3. **`IDisposable` added** — `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed. The original had no cleanup for `ManualResetEvent` either.

4. **Queue drain bug fixed** — the original could lose items: two rapid `Enqueue` calls set the event once, but only one `Dequeue` runs. The new code drains all pending items.

## Pitfalls to Watch

| Pitfall | Applies here? | Mitigation |
|---------|--------------|------------|
| `Handle()` runs for a long time, delaying cancellation | **Yes** — cancellation only checks between items | If `Handle` is long-running, pass the token into it and check periodically |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | **Yes** — common leak | `Stop()` calls `Dispose()`; also exposed via `IDisposable` |
| Calling `Stop()` twice | **Yes** — double-dispose | `CancellationTokenSource` tolerates double-dispose, but guard with a flag if `Stop` has other side effects |
| `Join(5000)` times out | **Possible** — if `Handle()` takes >5s | Consider `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `Handle`, or accept partial work |
